|identification_symbol_2= |identification_symbol_2_label= }} The 'Multi-National
Force â Iraq' ('MNFâI'), often referred to as the 'coalition forces', was a
military command during much of the Iraq War, that was led by the United States
of America and its allies. The MNF-I was responsible for conducting and handling
military operations during Operation Iraqi Freedom and for much of the Iraq War.
Multi-National Force â Iraq replaced the previous force, Combined Joint Task
Force 7, on 15 May 2004, and was later itself reorganized into its successor,
United States Forces â Iraq, on 1 January 2010. The Force was significantly
reinforced during the Iraq War troop surge of 2007. As of May 2011, all non-U.S.
coalition members had withdrawn from Iraq, [http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs-
/pdfs/9010_Report_to_CongressJul09.pdf 9010 DoD report, June 2009] with
the U.S. military withdrawing from the country on December 18, 2011, thus,
bringing about an end to the Iraq War.

Also in Iraq, since August 2003, is the United Nations Assistance Mission in
Iraq, which does humanitarian work and has a number of guards and military
observers. The U.N. Assistance Mission in Iraq was not a part of the MNF-I, but
a separate entity. The NATO Training Mission â Iraq, was in Iraq from 2004 to
December 2011, where it trained the Iraqi Army and the Iraqi police forces.
